======================================================================
PART 1: π IN MEAN(H) VIA STIRLING
======================================================================

  Mean(H) = n!/2^{n-1}  (the mean Hamiltonian path count)

  By Stirling: n! ~ √(2πn) · (n/e)^n

  So Mean(H) ~ √(2πn) · (n/e)^n / 2^{n-1}
             = √(2πn) · n^n / (e^n · 2^{n-1})
             = √(2πn) · 2 · (n/2e)^n

  The factor √(2π) is INTRINSIC to Mean(H).
  It comes from the Gaussian approximation to the binomial distribution
  of path choices.

  n= 3: Mean(H) =            1.50, Stirling =            1.46, ratio = 1.028065
  n= 4: Mean(H) =            3.00, Stirling =            2.94, ratio = 1.021008
  n= 5: Mean(H) =            7.50, Stirling =            7.38, ratio = 1.016784
  n= 6: Mean(H) =           22.50, Stirling =           22.19, ratio = 1.013973
  n= 7: Mean(H) =           78.75, Stirling =           77.82, ratio = 1.011968
  n= 8: Mean(H) =          315.00, Stirling =          311.74, ratio = 1.010466
  n= 9: Mean(H) =         1417.50, Stirling =         1404.44, ratio = 1.009298
  n=10: Mean(H) =         7087.50, Stirling =         7028.70, ratio = 1.008365
  n=11: Mean(H) =        38981.25, Stirling =        38687.13, ratio = 1.007602
  n=12: Mean(H) =       233887.50, Stirling =       232269.28, ratio = 1.006967
  n=13: Mean(H) =      1520268.75, Stirling =      1510556.51, ratio = 1.006430
  n=14: Mean(H) =     10641881.25, Stirling =     10578735.56, ratio = 1.005969

  As n→∞, the ratio → 1 (Stirling accuracy improves)
  The √(2π) factor is PERMANENT — it never cancels.

